{{italictitle}}
[[File:Johan_Christian_Clausen_Dahl_-_Et_søstykke._Kysterne_af_Rügen_set_i_aftenrøden_efter_en_stormfuld_dag_-_Statens_Museum_for_Kunst_-_KMS6852.jpeg|thumb|300px]]
'''''A Seascape. The Coast of the Island of Rügen in Evening Light'''''<ref name="kid">{{cite web|url=https://www.kulturarv.dk/kid/VisVaerk.do?vaerkId=405421|title=Kunstindeks Danmark & Weilbachs kunstnerleksikon|website=Kulturarv.dk|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> ({{lang-da|Et søstykke. Kysterne af Rügen set i aftenrøden efter en stormfuld dag}}, literally "A Seascape: The coast of Rügen seen in evening light after a stormy day") is an 1818 oil on canvas marine painting by [[J.C. Dahl]], measuring 37&nbsp;cm by 58.5&nbsp;cm and now in the [[Danish National Gallery]], which purchased it at auction in 1975. It was his first marine painting and the first work he produced in [[Dresden]]. A signed compositional drawing for it is now in the [[Bergen Museum of Art]].<ref name="utst">''Johan Christian Dahl 1788-1857: jubileumsutstilling 1988: Nasjonalgalleriet 27. februar-1. mai 1988, Bergen billedgalleri 19. mai-3. juli 1988'' (catalogue no. 25, p. 108) Oslo Nasjonalgalleriet 1988 {{ISBN|8290744056}}</ref>

The work is based on his eight-day journey from Denmark to Germany. He noted in his diary that a storm had come out of nowhere and not ceased before reaching Rügen, making him seasick throughout the voyage. The work was commissioned by [[Christian VIII of Denmark|Prince Christian Frederik]] in 1818 and Dahl was paid for the work in February 1819. After Christian Frederik's death in 1848 it was inherited by his son [[Frederick VI of Denmark|Frederik]], who immediately gave it to [[Louise Rasmussen|Countess Danner]]. After Frederik's death in 1863 it was sold at auction to a private collector in 1864.<ref name="utst" />

