{{Infobox person | name = Andrew Vicari | image =Andrew Vicari at the Celtic Manor.jpg | image_size = | caption = Vicari at the [[Celtic Manor]], Newport in 2007 | birth_name = | birth_date = 20 April 1932 | birth_place = [[Port Talbot]], Wales | death_date = 3 October 2016 (aged 84) | death_place = [[Morriston Hospital]], [[Swansea]], Wales | death_cause = | restingplace = | nationality = British | religion = | ethnicity = | residence = Monaco | education = [[Neath Grammar School]] | alma mater = [[Slade School of Fine Art]] | occupation = Artist | title = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | known for = | boards = | salary = | networth = £92 million (2006) | spouse = | parents = | children = | relations = | website = }}
[[Image:Vicari LaMarianne 240px.jpg|thumb|Painting by Andrew Vicari|260px|''La Marianne''(1980)]]
'''Andrew Vicari''' (born Andrea Antonio Giovanni Vaccari, 20 April 1932 – 3 October 2016) was a Welsh painter working in France, who established a career painting portraits of prominent people. Despite being largely unknown in his own country, {{As of|2004|lc=on}} Vicari was Britain's richest living painter,{{cn|date=October 2016}} and at one time Britain 18th richest person.<ref name="bbc.co.uk">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-37540601|title=Andrew Vicari the 'painter of kings' dies, aged 84|date=3 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=4 October 2016|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>
==Early life== Vicari was born in [[Port Talbot]], Wales, in 1932<ref>[http://www.southwales-eveningpost.co.uk/tributes-as-saudi-royal-artist-andrew-vicari-dies-at-home-in-wales/story-29773349-detail/story.html "Tributes as Saudi royal artist Andrew Vicari dies at home in Wales"], ''South Wales Evening Post'', 3 October 2016. Retrieved 6 October 2016.</ref> to Italian parents, Vittorio Vaccari ('tobacconist and confectioner'), and his wife, Italini Bertani, from [[Parma]].<ref name="king of painters">{{cite news|author=Stuart Jeffries |title='I am the king of painters' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2001/nov/16/arts.highereducation |work=[[The Guardian]] (G2) |date=16 November 2001 |accessdate=24 October 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/andrew-vicari-now-bankruptcy-proceedings-7989223 |title=Andrew Vicari now in bankruptcy proceedings |first=Robin |last=Turner |date=23 October 2014 |publisher= |accessdate=4 October 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005123530/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/andrew-vicari-now-bankruptcy-proceedings-7989223 |archivedate=5 October 2016 |df= }}</ref> He was evacuated to [[Aberdare]] during World War II. He later attended [[Neath Grammar School|Neath Grammar School for Boys]]. Aged 12 he won the Gold Medal for Painting at the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales|Wales National Eisteddfod]].<ref name="king of painters" /> Between 1950 and 1952 he studied painting at the [[Slade School of Fine Art]] at [[University College London]] (UCL) under [[William Coldstream]] and occasionally [[Lucian Freud]] as teachers. He had initially been refused a place at the Slade and was only admitted when someone dropped out.<ref name=NYT/>
==Career== After only two years, in 1952, Vicari left the Slade without completing his diploma course and went to Florence. He stayed there and in Rome for two years before returning 'penniless' to the UK<ref> Mills, John ''Which Yet Survive. Impressions of Friends, Family and Encounters'', Quartet Books, London 2017</ref>. He then began working in London as a portrait painter and in 1961 a large show of his work was put on in the former Debenhams showroom near Leicester Square financed by the band leader and impresario [[Jack Hylton]]. Eschewing modern trends, he remained a figurative artist working in oil. His work is appreciated worldwide, especially in the [[Middle East]] where three museums are solely dedicated to his work.
In 1974, Vicari was appointed as the official painter to the [[King of Saudi Arabia|King]] and [[Government of Saudi Arabia]].<ref name="king of painters" /> In the following decades, he painted many portraits of the [[House of Saud|Saudi royal family]] as well as scenes of [[Riyadh]] and [[Bedouin]] life. It is largely due to this patronage that Vicari owed his financial success and in 2011 earned him the title "The Rembrandt of Riyadh" from ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/30/magazine/30Vicari-t.html|title=The Rembrandt of Riyadh|date=27 January 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref> In 2001, he sold a collection of 125 paintings of the [[First Gulf War]] to Prince Khaled for £17 million.<ref name="bbc.co.uk"/>
==Personal life== Vicari lived and worked at his studio outside [[Nice]], France, although he also owned apartments in Riyadh and Monte Carlo.
In 2006 his fortune was valued at £92 million by the [[Sunday Times Rich List|''Sunday Times'' Rich List]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/section/0,,20590,00.html|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|publisher=|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref> In October 2014, however, it was reported that Vicari had filed for bankruptcy and had been in poor health.<ref name="WMail bankruptcy">{{cite news|last=Turner |first=Robin |title=Andrew Vicari now in bankruptcy proceedings |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/andrew-vicari-now-bankruptcy-proceedings-7989223 |work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]] |date=24 October 2014 |page=5 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005123530/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/andrew-vicari-now-bankruptcy-proceedings-7989223 |archivedate=5 October 2016 |df= }}</ref>
Vicari died at [[Morriston Hospital]], [[Swansea]] on 3 October 2016 at the age of 84.<ref name="bbc.co.uk"/>
