[[File:Pipa player - Yulin Cave 25.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Pipa]] player, south wall of Cave 25 ([[Tang Dynasty]])]] The '''Yulin Caves''' ({{zh|c={{linktext|榆|林|窟}}|p=Yulin kū}}) is a Buddhist cave temple site in [[Guazhou County]], [[Gansu Province]], China. The site is located some 100&nbsp;km east of the oasis town of [[Dunhuang]] and the [[Mogao Caves]]. It takes its name from the [[eponym]]ous [[elm]] trees lining the Yulin River, which flows through the site and separates the two cliffs from which the caves have been excavated. The forty-two caves house some 250 [[polychrome]] statues and 4,200 m<sup>2</sup> of wall paintings, dating from the [[Tang Dynasty]] to the [[Yuan Dynasty]] (seventh to fourteenth centuries).<ref name="Fan">{{cite book |title=安西榆林窟 The Anxi Yulin Grottoes |editor=Fan Jinshi |language=Chinese, English |publisher=Gansu National Publishing House |isbn=7542106465 |year=1999 |pages=6–9}}</ref><ref name="Yulin">{{cite book |script-title=zh:安西榆林窟 |trans-title=Anxi Yulin Caves |language=Chinese |editor=[[Mogao Caves|Dunhuang Academy]] |publisher=文物出版社 |year=1997 |isbn=7501007748}}</ref> The site was among the first to be designated for protection in 1961 as a [[Major Site Protected for Its Historical and Cultural Value at the National Level|Major National Historical and Cultural Site]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sach.gov.cn/tabid/96/InfoID/16/frtid/134/Default.aspx |title=国务院关于公布第一批全国重点文物保护单位名单的通知 (1st Designations) |date=3 April 1961 |publisher=[[State Administration of Cultural Heritage]] |language=Chinese |accessdate=27 April 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609132452/http://www.sach.gov.cn/tabid/96/InfoID/16/frtid/134/Default.aspx |archivedate=June 9, 2012 }}</ref> In 2008 the Yulin Grottoes were submitted for future inscription on the [[UNESCO World Heritage List]] as part of the Chinese Section of the [[Silk Road]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/5335/ |title=Chinese Section of the Silk Road |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref>
==Caves== Most of the caves take the form of an entrance corridor, antechamber, and main chamber. In three caves, a central pier was left intact during excavation then carved with niches on all four sides. A number of caves were reworked and repainted in later periods, since the site remained in use throughout the [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]], [[Five Dynasties]], [[Song Dynasty|Song]], [[Western Xia]], and [[Yuan Dynasty|Yuan]] Dynasties. It fell into disuse during the [[Ming Dynasty]]. There were early efforts to restore the caves at the time of the [[Qing Dynasty]] and several new caves also date to this period. More recently, under the management of the [[Mogao Caves|Dunhuang Academy]], the focus has been on [[preventive conservation]] through [[Geotechnical engineering|consolidation]] of the cliff face and [[Tourism in China|controlling access]].<ref name="Fan"/><ref name="Whitfield"/>
==Wall paintings== The paintings are [[Buddhist Art|Buddhist]] with some secular scenes, the former including [[buddhas]], [[bodhisattvas]], [[apsara]], and [[jataka tales]]; and the latter, [[donor portrait]]s, [[Go (game)|go]] players, representatives of [[Ethnic minorities in China|China's ethnic minorities]], marked out by their hair styles and dress, farming scenes such as milking a cow, wine-making, a smelting furnace, and a marriage ceremony; depictions of musicians and dancers help break down the distinction between the sacred and the profane.<ref name="Fan"/><ref name="Yulin"/> The paintings are not [[frescoes]] but instead executed on an earthen [[Plaster|render]] with mineral and organic [[pigments]] and [[Natural gum|gum]] or [[Animal glue|glue]] [[Binder (material)|binders]].<ref name="Whitfield">{{cite book |title=Cave Temples of Mogao: Art and History on the Silk Road |author=Whitfield, Roderick (''et al.'') |publisher=[[Getty Conservation Institute]] |year=2000 |isbn=0892365854 |pages=5, 114 ff, 135}}</ref>
==List of caves== The forty-two caves are dated as follows, based largely on the [[Style (visual arts)|style]] of the paintings and their accompanying [[Epigraphy|inscriptions]] (in [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]], [[Tibetan languages|Tibetan]], [[Sanskrit]], [[Tangut language|Tangut]], and [[Old Uighur language|Old Uighur]]):<ref>{{cite book |script-title=zh:安西榆林窟 |trans-title=Anxi Yulin Caves |language=Chinese |editor=[[Mogao Caves|Dunhuang Academy]] |publisher=文物出版社 |year=1997 |isbn=7501007748 |pages=254–263}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://hirosaki-u.academia.edu/DaiMatsui/Papers/1436663/Revising_the_Uigur_Inscriptions_of_the_Yulin_Caves |title=Revising the Uigur Inscriptions of the Yulin Caves |author=Dai Matsui |journal=Studies on the Inner Asian Languages |issn=1341-5670 |publisher=[[Osaka University]] |year=2008 |volume=23 |pages=17–33}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" style="width:100%; background:#fff;" |- !width="15%" align="left" style="background:#ffdead;" | Cave !width="20%" align="left" style="background:#ffdead;" | Construction !width="30%" align="left" style="background:#ffdead;" | Restorations !width="15%" align="left" style="background:#ffdead;" | Former Numbering !width="20%" align="left" style="background:#ffdead;" class="unsortable"| Image |- | Cave 1 || [[Qing Dynasty|Qing]] || || || |- | Cave 2 || [[Western Xia]] || [[Yuan Dynasty|Yuan]], [[Qing Dynasty|Qing]] || C1 || [[File:Yulin Cave 2 s wall preaching (Western Xia).jpg|100px]] |- | Cave 3 || [[Western Xia]] || [[Yuan Dynasty|Yuan]], [[Qing Dynasty|Qing]] || C2 || [[File:Yulin Cave 3 w wall Samantabhadra (Western Xia).jpg|100px]] |- | Cave 4 || [[Yuan Dynasty|Yuan]] || [[Qing Dynasty|Qing]] || C3 || [[File:Yulin Cave 4 e wall lokapala (Yuan).jpg|100px]] |- | Cave 5 || [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]] || [[Qing Dynasty|Qing]] || || [[File:Yulin Cave 5 antechamber s wall lokapala (Tang).jpg|100px]] |- | Cave 6 || [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]] || [[Five Dynasties]], [[S